Inspired by the above investigations, a string of ECL immunosensors based on Au NCs [71–78], Ag NCs [79,80] or Cu NCs [81] have been developed for protein detection. For example, Zhou et al. [82] employed BSA-stabilized Au25 NCs to simultaneously detect CEA and mucin 1 (MUC1, a transmembrane glycoprotein overexpressed in most tumor cells) by two different coreactants and coreaction accelerators in which the cross reactions of dual emitters for immunosensing of dual biomarkers were avoided slickly. In another work, Au NCs were linked with the coreaction accelerator, Pd@CuO, by the coreactant, tris(3-aminoethyl) amine (TAEA), and thus a dual self-catalysis nanostructure was formed in which the intramolecular coreaction between TAEA and Au NCs along with intramolecular coreactant acceleration between Pd@CuO and TAEA resulted in strong ECL emission for sensitive immunosensing of CEA (Fig. 1
                           ) [83]. Meanwhile, the one-step electrodeposition method was proposed to prepare Ag NCs and designed an ultrasensitive ECL immunosensor for determination of cyclin-1 (CCND1, an overexpressed protein in MCF-7 cell) [84]. Recently, the BSA-stabilized CuNCs with NIR emission was prepared for alpha-fetoprotein (AFP, a biomarker of primary liver cancer) detection, which provided an idea for employing non-noble metal NCs as luminophores [85]. Nowadays, the metal NC-based ECL emitters have been evolved from monometallic NCs to bimetallic NCs [86,87]. Taking AuAg NCs as examples, the doping of Ag into Met-stabilized Au NCs resulted in the red-shift of ECL wavelength from 806 nm of Au NCs to 906 nm of AgAu NCs, thus a spectrum-based ECL immunosensor was established for carbohydrate antigen (CA) CA125 (a sensitive biomarker of epithelial ovarian cancer and endometrial cancer) detection with a detection limit down to 5 × 10−5 U·mL−1 
                           [88]. Furthermore, by assembling ATT-stabilized Au NCs with ARG-stabilized Ag NCs via hydrogen bond [89], the resulted AuAg NCs super-molecule structure showed improved ECL efficiency due to aggregation induced enhancement (AIE) and silver synergistic catalysis, offering a special perspective for the development of metal NCs-based luminophore.
